# Hydra UX — composition and visual polish (within tokens)

**Language:** English (unless the user asks otherwise).

This rule **extends** **[hydra-ui-tokens.mdc](./hydra-ui-tokens.mdc)** and **[hydra-design-to-code.mdc](./hydra-design-to-code.mdc)**. It does **not** relax the ban on ad-hoc `#hex` / arbitrary design-intent `px` in screens.

## Intent

We may be **somewhat more creative** when it improves **clarity, hierarchy, and perceived quality** of the UX—as long as the implementation still traces to the design system.

## Composition

- **Combine existing building blocks** from **`src/ui/antd.ts`** (and established shell/layout patterns) when a single component is not enough.
- **Cards and grouped content:** It is fine to use **`Card`**, **`Space`**, **`Flex`**, **`Divider`**, **`Typography`**, **`Tag`**, etc., composed together to form **cards, panels, or summary strips**—including patterns that are not a single named “Card template” in Figma, as long as spacing, type, and colors come from **tokens** and **figmaTypography** as usual.
- Prefer **semantic theme tokens** (`colorBgContainer`, `colorBorderSecondary`, `colorFillAlter`, `padding*`, `margin*`, `borderRadius*`) for surfaces and grouping before reaching for primitives.

## Primitive colors (use with restraint)

- We may use **existing primitive / ramp colors** from the mirrored modules (e.g. **`primaryPrimitiveBlue`**, **`primaryPrimitiveOrange`**, **`buttonPrimaryPalette`**, **`figmaSemanticColors`**, and semantics that reference them) to add **accent, emphasis, or subtle variation**—for example a tinted header area, a soft border, or a highlight—**without overdoing it**.
- **Do not** introduce **new** arbitrary hex values in JSX/CSS for “prettier” UI; if something needs a recurring new color, follow **figma-repo-parity.mdc** (repo + Figma) or escalate.
- **Restraint:** Fewer strong colors beats noisy screens. Default to **neutral surfaces + one clear primary action**; use extra primitive-driven accents only when they **aid scanning or state** (e.g. risk, success, section identity).

## Checklist

- [ ] Creativity serves **UX** (hierarchy, grouping, feedback)—not decoration for its own sake.
- [ ] Composition uses **barrel + tokens**; typography still from **figmaTypography** / **theme** only.
- [ ] Any primitive-based color is **imported from allowed mirror modules** or exposed via **theme**, not pasted literals.
- [ ] Visual noise is **limited**; the screen still feels like **Hydra / Ant Design**.

